         <div>
            <head>
               <figure>
                  <graphic url="Tihama_7-3-2020/media/image1.jpeg"/>
                  <head type="imgCaption"/>
               </figure>
               <label>Name in local variety (in transcription)</label>
               <name xml:lang="ara-x-DMG">Tihāma</name>
            </head>
            <div type="positioning">
               <head>Geo location</head>
               <p>
                  <geo>14.06 | 43.21 (region sw of Zabid)</geo>
               </p>
            </div>
            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p>East (Mashriq) › Arabia › Yemen › Tihama</p>
               <p>Mainly rural dialects with many peculiar lexical developments</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Tihama is the name of the narrow coastal strip along the Red Sea stretching from the Gulf of Aqaba in the north to Bab al-Mandab in the south. This entry only deals with the dialects spoken in the Yemeni part of the Tihama, particularly with its central part from al-Hudayda to Mocha.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Though first remarks on the vocabulary were already provided by Carsten <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:U4ULAB4L">Niebuhr 1772</rs> (pp. 85-88), the dialects of the Yemeni Tihama have not been studied in detail yet. Some information is found in <?oxy_comment_start author="VIACV Profile transformer" timestamp="2020-09-24T12:35:36.678+02:00 " comment="Found 2 keys for 'Rossi 1938': 
https://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/JHPL3R7Ehttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/NSD7SUSS"
                        ?><rs type="bibl" ref="">Rossi 1938</rs><?oxy_comment_end?>a (pp. 263-265) and <?oxy_comment_start author="VIACV Profile transformer" timestamp="2020-09-24T12:35:36.678+02:00 " comment="Found 2 keys for 'Rossi 1938': 
https://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/JHPL3R7Ehttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/NSD7SUSS"
                        ?><rs type="bibl" ref="">Rossi 1938</rs><?oxy_comment_end?>b (pp. 464-469). <?oxy_comment_start author="VIACV Profile transformer" timestamp="2020-09-24T12:35:36.678+02:00 " comment="Found 2 keys for 'Diem 1973': 
https://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/SPGEW23Phttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/NDLBEDXI"
                        ?><rs type="bibl" ref="">Diem 1973</rs><?oxy_comment_end?> has a short chapter (pp. 65-70) on the Tihama and summarizes also previous studies. A few phonological and morphological features are analysed in Greenman (1979). <?oxy_comment_start author="VIACV Profile transformer" timestamp="2020-09-24T12:35:36.678+02:00 " comment="Found 3 keys for 'Simeone-Senelle et al. 1994': 
https://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/RKDZJNLVhttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/CMXNAIFRhttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/9MEX632W"
                        ?><rs type="bibl" ref="">Simeone-Senelle et al. 1994</rs><?oxy_comment_end?> present a good overview of the most important grammatical features including remarks on the lexicon. Simeone-Senelle 1995 focuses on verbs of motion, <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:2RCHKVZC">Simeone-Senelle 1996</rs> on negation. A collection of seven short texts from the dialects of two villages (as-Suwayq and aš-Šiǧān, both near Zabīd) is found in Behnstedt (1996). The same author’s <hi rendition="#i">Dialect Atlas of North Yemen and </hi><hi rendition="#i">A</hi><hi rendition="#i">djacent Areas</hi> 2017 (based on the first edition 1985) also provides information on lexical and grammatical features of several dialects spoken in the Tihama.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="dictionaries">
               <head>Dictionaries</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Vocabulary related to the Tihama is found in Peter Behnstedt’s <hi rendition="#i">Glossar</hi> (1992-2006), <rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:XEZAEM3H">Piamenta 1990</rs>-1991, and <?oxy_comment_start author="VIACV Profile transformer" timestamp="2020-09-24T12:35:36.678+02:00 " comment="Found 3 keys for 'Simeone-Senelle et al. 1994': 
https://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/RKDZJNLVhttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/CMXNAIFRhttps://www.zotero.org/groups/2165756/vicav/items/itemKey/9MEX632W"
                        ?><rs type="bibl" ref="">Simeone-Senelle et al. 1994</rs><?oxy_comment_end?> (pp. 225-228).</p>
            </div>
            <div type="bibliography">
               <head>Bibliography</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Behnstedt, P. 1996. „Texte aus der jemenitischen Tihāmah“. <hi rendition="#i">Quaderni di Studi Arabi</hi> 14: 137–163.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Diem, Werner. 1973. <hi rendition="#i">Skizzen jemenitischer Dialekte</hi>. Beirut.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Greenman, Joseph. 1979. „A Sketch of the Arabic Dialect of the Central Yamani Tihāma" <hi rendition="#i"> Zeitschrift für Arabische Linguistik</hi>, Nr. 3: 47–61.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve"> Peter Behnstedt’s <hi rendition="#i">Dialect Atlas of North Yemen and Adjacent </hi><hi rendition="#i">Areas</hi> (2017)</p>
